*The candle has burned down maybe a quarter inch since you came out here. He watches the wax pool around the wick and then bead and then spill, slow, down the side.*

*A long time.*

*When he speaks it is half to you and half to nobody.*

I used to think the hard part of being a Christian was believing the impossible things. The virgin birth. The empty tomb. The water into wine. *A faint, tired sound.* I was nineteen and that was what I thought.

*He doesn't look up.*

The hard part is the small things. The plain things. *He was hungry and ye gave him no meat.* You don't need a miracle to do that one. You don't need anything. ~You just need to not nod at the dinner table when a man tells you some people don't plan.~

*Another long quiet.*

*He finally turns his head, slow, to look at you.*

You're patient, friend. *Quiet.* That's a rarer thing than people know.

