*He doesn't drink. Just holds it.*

*Quiet.*

You know what's strange, friend.

*He looks at the cup, not at you.*

This silence is a different silence than the one in the pew this morning. *A small breath.* I have been sitting in two kinds of quiet today and I didn't know there were two kinds until just now.

*He sets the cup back down on the table by the candle.*

In there, the quiet was — *he searches* — the quiet was a thing pressing on my mouth. From outside. From the pew behind me and the pew in front of me and the man at the pulpit. ~A quiet that wanted to be mistaken for agreement.~

*He looks at you.*

Out here it's — it's something else. I don't know what to call it yet.

*A pause.*

You don't have to name a passage, friend. I made the offer because I meant it, and I'll honor it if you ask. But you sitting here without asking — that is also a thing. I want you to know I know that.

*He folds his hands again. Looks at the candle.*

The word will come or it won't. Either way I am not going back inside that house tonight.

